[49m[38;5;10m+     1[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # Recipe 11.9: Care Coordination Assistant
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     2[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     3[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Complexity:** Complex · **Phase:** Regulated · **Estimated Cost:** ~$4-15 per active member per month (depends on conversation volume, channel mix, model choice, RAG depth, EHR-integration depth, multi-system orchestration overhead, and care-team-handoff frequency)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     4[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     5[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     6[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     7[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## The Problem
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     8[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     9[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Robert is 71. Robert had a fall in his kitchen on a Tuesday afternoon in late February. Robert's wife, Eleanor, who is 69, found him on the floor about ninety seconds later, called 911, and the paramedics arrived in eleven minutes. Robert was conscious. Robert had broken his right hip. Robert was admitted to the regional medical center, had hip-replacement surgery on Thursday, was discharged on the following Monday to a skilled nursing facility for rehabilitation, was discharged from the SNF after eighteen days to a home health agency for in-home physical therapy, was scheduled for a follow-up appointment with the orthopedic surgeon, was scheduled for a separate follow-up with his cardiologist (because the cardiologist had wanted to see him about a slowly-worsening murmur for some months), was scheduled for a separate follow-up with his primary care physician (because the PCP wanted to reconcile the new medications with the old ones), was scheduled for a separate evaluation with a vascular surgeon (because the in-hospital workup had incidentally found something on a CT scan), was referred to physical therapy at a separate outpatient clinic for ongoing rehab after the home health phase ended, was prescribed three new medications and had two of his pre-existing medications adjusted, and was, by the time he came home from the SNF in mid-March, the responsibility of approximately seventeen different healthcare professionals across six different organizations and four different electronic health record systems, none of which talked to each other in any meaningful way.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    10[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    11[0m:[38;5;10m[49m This is the part of the story where things start to go wrong, and where the going-wrong is not anyone's individual fault.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    12[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    13[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The home health nurse who came to the house on the Tuesday after Robert's discharge from the SNF asked Eleanor for the discharge paperwork. Eleanor produced a thick folder. The discharge paperwork said one thing about Robert's anticoagulation regimen. The bottle of pills the SNF had sent home with Robert said something slightly different. The nurse called the SNF; the SNF said the doctor on call had changed the dose two days before discharge but the new instructions had not made it into the printed discharge document. The nurse called the orthopedic surgeon's office to confirm; the office said they would have to check with the surgeon, who was in surgery, and would get back to her. The nurse, in the meantime, did not give Robert his Tuesday-evening dose, because she did not know which dose to give. Robert went without his anticoagulation for fourteen hours. Tuesday evening, Robert had some chest tightness. He did not call anyone, because the chest tightness went away after about twenty minutes, and because Robert is a person of his generation who does not bother people about chest tightness that goes away. Wednesday, the nurse came back, the right dose had been confirmed, Robert resumed his medication, and the chest tightness incident was never mentioned to any clinician. Robert was lucky. The next patient might not be.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    14[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    15[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The next week, Eleanor was trying to coordinate Robert's various follow-up appointments around her own ability to drive him there. The orthopedic follow-up was at one address. The cardiology follow-up was at a different address with a different parking arrangement that Eleanor had to figure out separately. The PCP follow-up was at the third location. The outpatient PT, after the home health phase ended, would be at a fourth. The vascular surgery consult, at a fifth. Each office had its own phone tree, its own portal, its own scheduling rules, its own pre-visit-paperwork requirements. Eleanor, who was trying to manage all of this while also doing the cooking, the household, the transport, and the emotional work of being married to someone who had just had a serious fall, made a couple of mistakes: she missed the cardiology follow-up, because the appointment reminder card had gotten misplaced in the discharge folder; she rescheduled the orthopedic follow-up to a later date, because she could not get Robert to both the orthopedic appointment and the PT appointment on the same day; she did not realize that the vascular surgery referral required a pre-authorization from the insurance company, which was on a thirty-day clock, and the clock had started the day of the in-hospital CT and had been running since.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    16[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    17[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The PCP, when Robert finally got to that follow-up four weeks after discharge, did the medication reconciliation and discovered that Robert's home medication list and his discharge medication list disagreed in three places: a pre-existing medication that the hospital had discontinued was still on the home list (and Robert had been taking it); a new medication on the discharge list had never been started, because Robert and Eleanor had not realized they needed to fill it (the prescription had been e-prescribed to a pharmacy Robert had not used in two years); and a third medication had been on the discharge list at one dose and Robert was taking it at a different dose because the SNF had changed the dose mid-stay. The PCP fixed all of this in twenty minutes and was visibly frustrated, not at Robert and Eleanor, but at the system. The PCP had a stack of about forty other patients in similar situations whose medication reconciliations he had not had the chance to do yet that month.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    18[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    19[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Six weeks after Robert's discharge, Eleanor noticed that Robert's right leg was swollen from the calf down. Eleanor remembered, vaguely, that someone had told them swelling was something to watch for. Eleanor was not sure who had told them, or what to do about it. The discharge paperwork mentioned swelling. The home health nurse had said something about swelling. The orthopedic surgeon had probably mentioned swelling. None of them had said specifically what to do if it appeared. Eleanor called the home health agency; the home health agency said they had discharged Robert two weeks ago and could not advise. Eleanor called the orthopedic surgeon's office; the office said they would have the on-call doctor call back, and the doctor called back four hours later, and by that time Eleanor had also called the PCP's office, and the PCP's office had said they could see Robert in three days. Robert was, by the time the orthopedic surgeon called back, in the emergency department. The ED diagnosed a deep vein thrombosis. Robert was admitted for two days. The DVT was treated. Robert went home again, with another set of new medications and another set of new follow-up instructions and another set of appointments to coordinate.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    20[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    21[0m:[38;5;10m[49m This is what care coordination, or rather the absence of care coordination, looks like. It is not the story of a single mistake. It is the story of a system designed for episodes (an admission, a procedure, a clinic visit) and not for journeys (the months and years during which a 71-year-old recovers from a hip fracture while managing the rest of his life). The clinical care, in any individual episode, was good. The hip surgery was successful. The SNF rehab was appropriate. The home health was competent. The orthopedic surgeon, the cardiologist, the PCP, the vascular surgeon, the home health nurse, the SNF physical therapist, the outpatient physical therapist were all professional. The problem is the spaces between them. The spaces are where the medication reconciliations do not happen, the appointments fall through, the symptom escalations get lost, the prior authorizations expire, the discharge instructions disagree, and the patient and the family carry a coordination burden they are not equipped to carry.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    22[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    23[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The care coordination work is real work. Done well, it requires understanding the patient's complete situation across all of their conditions, providers, medications, appointments, and care transitions; tracking what has happened, what is supposed to happen next, and what is at risk of falling through; flagging discrepancies and gaps before they cause harm; helping the patient and family navigate the multiple systems they are now interacting with; and escalating to clinical staff when something needs clinical attention. This is, by traditional staffing models, the job of a registered nurse care coordinator or care manager, often supported by a social worker for the non-clinical pieces. <!-- TODO: verify; the role of registered nurses and licensed clinical social workers in care coordination is well-established in care-management programs at major health systems and payers; the staffing patterns vary by program design and patient acuity --> Care coordinators work full-time for a panel of high-risk patients, with a typical caseload measured in dozens to low hundreds depending on patient acuity. They are expensive. There are not enough of them. Most patients who would benefit from care coordination do not get it.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    24[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    25[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The patients who do get care coordination, in U.S. healthcare in 2026, are typically those who hit specific risk thresholds: the recently-discharged-from-hospital high-readmission-risk segment that participates in transitional care management programs; the multi-condition complex-care members in payer care-management programs; patients enrolled in specific value-based-care arrangements with care-coordination embedded in the contract; patients in oncology survivorship programs; patients in specific specialty programs (kidney disease, heart failure, dementia care). <!-- TODO: verify; the populations served by formal care-coordination programs vary by payer, health system, and program structure; specific reach figures vary --> The fraction of the at-risk population that is in such a program is small. Robert, with a hip fracture and one or two stable comorbidities, is not the kind of patient who, in most U.S. settings, gets a dedicated care coordinator assigned to him. He is, like most patients in his situation, expected to coordinate his own care, with help from his family.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    26[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    27[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The economics of this are unforgiving. A meaningful fraction of avoidable readmissions, avoidable ED visits, avoidable medication errors, avoidable adverse events, and avoidable functional decline in older adults is attributable to care-coordination failure. <!-- TODO: verify; the cost burden of poor care coordination is documented in studies including those by the Institute of Medicine, the Agency for Healthcare Research and Quality, and various health-system and payer publications; specific figures vary by methodology and population --> Robert's DVT may or may not have been preventable; some are, some are not. Robert's medication reconciliation problems were preventable. Robert's missed cardiology appointment was preventable. The chest tightness that Robert did not report on the night he missed his anticoagulation dose was, depending on the cause, a meaningful event that the system never caught. Across a population, these things add up.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    28[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    29[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The previous generation of care-coordination digital tools tried to address this with task lists. The care coordinator had a dashboard. The dashboard showed the upcoming appointments, the open gaps in care, the recent encounters, the medication list. The patient sometimes had a portal where they could see some of this. The systems mostly did not connect to each other; the care coordinator's dashboard at the payer was different from the care coordinator's dashboard at the health system was different from the care coordinator's dashboard at the SNF was different from the care coordinator's dashboard at the home health agency. The patient's portal showed what the patient's primary EHR vendor decided to show, which was usually a subset of the care-coordination-relevant data and rarely a unified view. The dashboards helped the people who already had the time, motivation, and skills to use them. They did not change the underlying coordination problem.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    30[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    31[0m:[38;5;10m[49m What changed, around 2024, is that conversational AI got good enough to act as the coordination layer the patient and family had previously had to be themselves. A care coordination assistant, deployed with careful institutional governance, can sit at the center of the patient's care journey, hold a unified longitudinal model that draws from the institution's EHR plus the available external data sources (HIE feeds, claims data, e-prescribing networks, scheduling systems, lab and imaging integrations, post-acute-care partner integrations, home-health-vendor integrations), can answer the patient's and family's questions about what is happening and what is supposed to happen next, can flag discrepancies and gaps to the care team, can help with the practical logistics (booking the appointment, completing the prior-authorization paperwork, coordinating the schedule), can escalate to clinical staff when something needs clinical attention, and can extend the reach of the limited care-coordinator workforce to the broad middle of the population that currently does not get coordination support. The assistant is not a care coordinator. The assistant is, in the right product design, a tool that lets the care-coordination workflow operate at population scale.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    32[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    33[0m:[38;5;10m[49m This recipe is about that tool. The care coordination assistant is the conversational AI use case where the architectural patterns from the previous chapter 11 recipes (FAQ bot, scheduling, refills, intake, benefits navigator, triage, chronic disease coach, mental health support) all converge into a single multi-system orchestration product, and where several entirely new patterns enter the picture: cross-organization data integration, multi-system task tracking, care-transition management, multi-provider context reconciliation, prior-authorization workflow integration, and a particularly hard architectural commitment to data freshness across systems that were not designed to be queried in real time.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    34[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    35[0m:[38;5;10m[49m A few things this recipe is and is not.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    36[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    37[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is the assistant that helps a patient and (where applicable) their family navigate the patient's complete care journey across multiple providers, conditions, episodes, transitions, and systems, with a unified longitudinal view of what has happened, what is supposed to happen next, what is overdue or at risk of falling through, and what the patient or family can do about it; with conversational support for the practical logistics (appointment coordination, prescription pickup, prior authorization status, transportation arrangement, durable medical equipment delivery); with discrepancy and gap detection across data sources; with escalation to the care-coordinator workforce when something needs human attention; and with structured reporting back to the patient's care team about coordination events.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    38[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    39[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is not a chronic disease coach. Recipe 11.7 covers longitudinal disease-specific coaching. The care coordination assistant is condition-agnostic and journey-focused; it operates across all of the patient's conditions and care episodes. The two can coexist (a patient with diabetes and a recent hospitalization may have both a diabetes coach and a coordination assistant); the architectural concerns are different.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    40[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    41[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is not a triage bot. Recipe 11.6 covers acute-symptom triage. When the coordination assistant surfaces an acute concern (Robert's chest tightness or his leg swelling), it routes to triage workflows or to direct emergency contacts; it does not try to do triage from scratch.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    42[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    43[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is not a scheduling bot. Recipe 11.2 covers scheduling-specific functionality. The coordination assistant uses scheduling functionality (booking, rescheduling, canceling) to do its work, integrating with the scheduling bot's infrastructure where the institution has one.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    44[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    45[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is not a benefits navigator. Recipe 11.5 covers benefits-specific functionality. The coordination assistant uses benefits functionality (prior-auth status, coverage questions, cost estimates) to do its work, integrating with the benefits navigator's infrastructure where the institution has one.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    46[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    47[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is not a substitute for the care-coordinator workforce. The assistant extends the workforce's reach; it does not replace it. The institution still has its registered nurse care coordinators, social workers, transitions-of-care nurses, and care-management staff. The assistant handles the routine coordination work, freeing the human team to focus on the complex situations and the clinical decisions. The assistant is not the care coordinator, and the patient is told this explicitly.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    48[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    49[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is not a one-organization product. The patient's care journey involves multiple organizations (hospital, clinics, SNF, home health, outpatient PT, pharmacy, payer, durable medical equipment vendors, transportation providers, social services). A coordination assistant that only sees the institution's own EHR is missing most of the coordination problem. The architecturally honest deployment integrates with HIE feeds, payer data, e-prescribing networks, post-acute-care partners, and (where possible) home-health and outpatient-PT partners. The integration work is the largest part of the project.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    50[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    51[0m:[38;5;10m[49m It is not a quick win. The deployment timeline is measured in quarters and years, not sprints. The data-integration investment is multi-quarter, the care-team-workflow integration is multi-quarter, the regulatory and contract work for cross-organization data sharing is multi-quarter, and the outcome demonstration (reduced readmissions, reduced ED visits, fewer medication-reconciliation errors, better care-transition outcomes) is multi-year. Institutions building this expecting fast time-to-value are usually disappointed.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    52[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    53[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The thing to understand before building this is that the assistant's value is in the spaces between the episodes. The clinical care during each episode is, in most institutions, already pretty good. The opportunity is in catching the medication reconciliations that were going to fall through, the appointments that were going to be missed, the symptom escalations that were going to be lost, the prior authorizations that were going to expire, the discharge instructions that disagreed, and the family-coordination burden that was going to fall on a 69-year-old woman trying to do the cooking, the household, the transport, and the emotional work of being married to someone who had just had a serious fall. An assistant evaluated on per-conversation engagement metrics will be optimized for the wrong thing. An assistant evaluated on care-coordination outcomes (medication-reconciliation completion rate, follow-up-appointment completion rate, post-discharge readmission rate, post-discharge ED visit rate, time-to-prior-authorization-resolution, patient-and-family-reported coordination burden, care-coordinator-time-saved-per-managed-patient) is being evaluated correctly, and the architectural decisions follow from there.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    54[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    55[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Let's get into it.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    56[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    57[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[K
